\begin{abstract}
Bayesian shrinkage priors offer an appealing alternative to frequentist regularization by providing automatic penalty learning and full uncertainty quantification. Yet their practical performance under model misspecification remains underexamined. The present simulation study benchmarked three Bayesian priors---horseshoe, Laplace (Bayesian lasso), and normal (ridge-type)---implemented via mean-field variational inference in \texttt{rstanarm}, across sample sizes of $n = 500$, $n = 2{,}000$, and $n = 10{,}000$ with $p = 2{,}000$ predictors. Data were generated under a correctly specified linear model (Layer~1) and a compound misspecification incorporating quadratic effects, threshold effects, interactions, and heteroscedastic noise (Layer~2). Predictive accuracy ($R^2$, RMSE), variable selection (95\% credible intervals), and selection stability (mean pairwise Jaccard index) were evaluated over 30 replications. At $n = 10{,}000$, horseshoe and Laplace priors achieved moderate predictive accuracy ($R^2 > .55$) in both layers, whereas the normal prior failed catastrophically at all sample sizes. However, all priors selected nearly all predictors regardless of sample size or layer, which rendered variable selection uninformative. Stability was high but merely reflected the pervasive selection of almost all variables. These findings indicate that default variational inference with \texttt{rstanarm} can yield robust prediction in high dimensions under misspecification when sample sizes are large, but is unreliable for variable selection without careful tuning or more accurate posterior approximations. Applied researchers should critically evaluate the interplay between prior specification, approximate inference, and analytic goals when deploying Bayesian shrinkage methods.
\end{abstract}

\noindent\textbf{Keywords:} Bayesian statistics; variational inference; Monte Carlo simulation; model misspecification; shrinkage priors; high-dimensional regression

%-----------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Introduction}

Modern predictive modeling in psychology and the social sciences increasingly relies on high-dimensional regularized regression. Yet most empirical and methodological work still evaluates methods under well-specified linear models, even though real data frequently violate linearity, homoscedasticity, and additivity. Building on our prior simulation benchmark of frequentist regularization under compound misspecification, the present paper develops a parallel Bayesian benchmark using variational inference and a range of shrinkage priors.

Regularized regression (ridge, lasso, elastic net, and related methods) is now routine, but its robustness is usually assessed assuming correct model specification. The earlier work documented how convex and non-convex penalties (ridge, LASSO, elastic net, adaptive LASSO, SCAD, MCP) degrade when nonlinearity, heteroscedasticity, and omitted interactions are jointly present, under realistic high-dimensional designs and sample sizes $^{1}$. This highlighted that applied users need guidance not only on tuning, but on method choice when models are wrong.

Bayesian penalized regression replaces penalty terms with shrinkage priors such as Normal, Laplace (Bayesian lasso), horseshoe, and spike-and-slab, often yielding competitive or superior prediction and variable selection, with automatic penalty learning and full uncertainty quantification $^{2}$. Carefully designed global--local priors (e.g., horseshoe) can combine near-optimal contraction and variable-selection consistency with practical gains over LASSO-type regularization $^{3}$. Exact Bayesian inference is often computationally prohibitive; variational inference (VI) provides scalable approximate posteriors by turning integration into optimization $^{4}$. Mean-field and related VI schemes have been developed for high-dimensional linear regression with product priors and can be accurate under suitable conditions $^{5}$. User-friendly implementations, such as \texttt{rstanarm}, now expose these ideas to applied researchers $^{2}$.

Bayesian shrinkage methods offer several attractions whether or not the linear model is correct. Under approximate sparsity and correct specification, heavy-tailed priors like the horseshoe and spike-and-slab achieve near-optimal recovery and valid uncertainty, sometimes outperforming frequentist regularization in variable selection and inference $^{3,6}$. Under heavy-tailed errors or robust loss formulations, horseshoe-type priors can still deliver valid credible intervals and strong selection performance $^{7}$. At the same time, generalized and nonparametric Bayesian frameworks have begun to address model misspecification more directly, targeting robustness when both the regression function and error structure are imperfectly modeled $^{8}$. These developments motivate a systematic empirical comparison of practical Bayesian shrinkage implementations, such as \texttt{rstanarm} with Normal, Laplace, horseshoe, and spike-and-slab priors, against frequentist regularization when the data-generating process is deliberately and severely misspecified, extending our previous benchmarking study into the Bayesian domain.

