\section{Methods}

\subsection{Data Generation}

Data were generated from a linear model with correlated predictors. The predictor vector $\mathbf{x} \in \mathbb{R}^p$ with $p = 2{,}000$ was drawn from a multivariate normal distribution with mean zero and block-diagonal covariance matrix $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$:
\[
\mathbf{x} \sim \mathcal{N}(\mathbf{0}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}).
\]
The covariance structure comprised $B = p/20 = 100$ independent blocks of size 20. Within each block the correlation between any two predictors was $\rho = 0.4$, yielding
\[
\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_b = \rho \mathbf{J}_{20} + (1-\rho)\mathbf{I}_{20}, \quad b = 1,\ldots,B,
\]
and $\boldsymbol{\Sigma} = \operatorname{blockdiag}(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_1, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_2, \ldots, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_B)$, where $\mathbf{J}_{20}$ is the $20\times 20$ matrix of ones and $\mathbf{I}_{20}$ the $20\times 20$ identity matrix.

The coefficient vector $\boldsymbol{\beta} = (\beta_1, \ldots, \beta_p)^\top$ was fixed across all replications. Ten percent of the predictors (200 variables) were assigned larger effects, and the remaining 90\% (1,800 variables) smaller effects. Specifically, letting the set of large-effect indices be a random sample of size $0.1p$ and the rest be the small-effect indices:
\[
\beta_j = \begin{cases} 
s_j u_j, & j \in \text{large},\ \text{where } u_j \sim \mathrm{Unif}(0.2, 0.5),\ s_j \in \{-1, 1\} \text{ with equal probability},\\
s_j v_j, & j \in \text{small},\ \text{where } v_j \sim \mathrm{Unif}(0.01, 0.1).
\end{cases}
\]

The signal-to-noise ratio was controlled via a base error standard deviation $\sigma_{\text{base}} = 0.5$.

\subsection{Misspecification Layers}

For the correctly specified model, the noise was homoscedastic: $\varepsilon \sim \mathcal{N}(0, \sigma^2)$, $\sigma = \sigma_{\text{base}} \cdot \mathrm{sd}(\mathbf{X}\boldsymbol{\beta})$, which yields a theoretical $R^2 \approx 0.8$. The outcome under the well-specified linear model (Layer~1) is therefore
\[
y_{\text{base}} = \mathbf{x}^\top\boldsymbol{\beta} + \varepsilon.
\]

To study robustness under model misspecification, a second outcome variable was constructed (Layer~2) that added three forms of nonlinearity and heteroscedasticity to the linear predictor $\mu = \mathbf{x}^\top\boldsymbol{\beta}$.

\paragraph{Quadratic effects.} Quadratic effects were included on 50 randomly chosen predictors. Letting $\mathcal{Q}$ denote this set ($|\mathcal{Q}| = 50$) and drawing coefficients $\gamma_q \sim \mathrm{Unif}(-0.05, 0.05)$:
\[
\text{Quadratic effect} = \sum_{q \in \mathcal{Q}} \gamma_q X_q^2.
\]

\paragraph{Threshold effects.} Threshold (step-function) effects were introduced on 20 distinct predictors. With $\mathcal{T}$ the set of threshold variables ($|\mathcal{T}| = 20$) and $\delta_t \sim \mathrm{Unif}(-0.2, 0.2)$:
\[
\text{Threshold effect} = \sum_{t \in \mathcal{T}} \delta_t \mathbf{1}(X_t > 0).
\]

\paragraph{Interaction effects.} One hundred within-block pairwise interactions were added. From all possible pairs within the same block, 100 pairs were randomly selected. Denoting the chosen pairs by $(i_m, j_m)$ and their coefficients by $\theta_m \sim \mathrm{Unif}(-0.1, 0.1)$:
\[
\text{Interaction effect} = \sum_{m=1}^{100} \theta_m X_{i_m} X_{j_m}.
\]

Finally, the error term was made heteroscedastic, with its standard deviation scaling linearly with the absolute value of the linear predictor:
\[
\varepsilon_{\text{het}} \sim \mathcal{N}\!\left(0,\ \sigma^2 \cdot \frac{|\mu|}{\mathrm{sd}(\mu)}\right),
\]
where $\mu$ denotes the linear predictor. The full misspecified outcome is
\[
y_{\text{compound}} = \mathbf{x}^\top\boldsymbol{\beta} + \sum_{q \in \mathcal{Q}} \gamma_q X_q^2 + \sum_{t \in \mathcal{T}} \delta_t \mathbf{1}(X_t > 0) + \sum_{m=1}^{100} \theta_m X_{i_m} X_{j_m} + \varepsilon_{\text{het}}.
\]

All non-linear structures (quadratic, threshold, and interaction terms) as well as the coefficient vector $\boldsymbol{\beta}$ were held constant across the $R = 30$ simulation replications. The only randomness between replications arose from the generation of $\mathbf{X}$ and the noise terms. Three sample sizes were considered: $n \in \{500, 2{,}000, 10{,}000\}$. For each replication and sample size, the largest necessary dataset was generated first and then the first $n$ rows were extracted, ensuring that comparisons across $n$ within a replication used overlapping observations.

\subsection{Analytical Approach}

\subsubsection{Analyses}

Three Bayesian penalized regression models were fitted to each dataset. All models used the same linear form $y = \beta_0 + \mathbf{x}^\top\boldsymbol{\beta} + \varepsilon$, but differed in the prior placed on the regression coefficients $\boldsymbol{\beta} = (\beta_1, \ldots, \beta_p)^\top$. The priors were as follows.

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Normal prior (ridge-type):} $\beta_j \sim \mathcal{N}(0, 2.5^2)$ with automatic rescaling of the prior scale based on the data $^{9}$.
  \item \textbf{Horseshoe prior} $^{10}$: a global--local shrinkage prior defined hierarchically by
  \[
  \beta_j \mid \lambda_j, \tau \sim \mathcal{N}(0, \lambda_j^2 \tau^2), \quad \lambda_j \sim C^+(0, 1), \quad \tau \sim C^+(0, 1).
  \]
  The prior was implemented via the regularized horseshoe $^{11}$ with tail heaviness controlled by a slab with scale 2.5 and degrees of freedom 4.
  \item \textbf{Laplace prior (lasso-type)} $^{12}$: $\beta_j \sim \mathrm{Laplace}(0, 1)$, inducing a Bayesian lasso with automatic scale adjustment.
\end{itemize}

For all models, the intercept $\beta_0$ was given a flat improper prior. The error variance $\sigma_\varepsilon^2$ was assigned the default weakly informative prior of the \texttt{stan\_glm} function (an exponential prior on $\sigma_\varepsilon$ with rate $1/\mathrm{sd}(y)$).

\subsubsection{Variational Inference}

Traditional Bayesian inference often relies on conjugate models, which permit closed-form posterior updates for specific prior--likelihood pairs, or on Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) to approximate the posterior distribution when such closed forms are unavailable $^{13,14,15,16}$. Conjugate models allow fast analytical computation of posteriors but are limited in flexibility because they require particular combinations of priors and likelihoods $^{13,14,17,15,16}$.

MCMC algorithms instead construct a Markov chain whose iterates are samples from (or asymptotically converge to) the posterior and use these samples to approximate posterior quantities, enabling inference for complex and high-dimensional models that lack conjugate structure $^{18,19,20,21,22,23}$. However, MCMC is often computationally costly because it requires many sequential iterations and careful convergence assessment, and it can scale poorly with model complexity, data size, or dimensionality $^{18,19,20,21,24,22,25}$. In high-dimensional settings, where the main goal may be to efficiently identify relevant predictors or obtain approximate uncertainty quantification rather than exact posterior inference, such computational costs can make MCMC unattractive $^{24,18,19}$. In these cases, variational inference (VI) provides a scalable alternative that approximates the posterior by solving an optimization problem, typically achieving substantial speedups relative to MCMC while retaining useful Bayesian features, albeit with potential losses in accuracy and underestimation of uncertainty $^{24,18,26,19,13,22,27,25}$.

Variational inference reframes posterior approximation as an optimization problem. Let $p(\boldsymbol{\theta} \mid \mathbf{y})$ denote the true posterior, which is typically intractable due to the normalizing constant $p(\mathbf{y}) = \int p(\mathbf{y} \mid \boldsymbol{\theta})\, p(\boldsymbol{\theta})\, d\boldsymbol{\theta}$. VI introduces a family of tractable approximating distributions $\mathcal{Q} = \{q(\boldsymbol{\theta}; \boldsymbol{\lambda})\}$, parameterized by variational parameters $\boldsymbol{\lambda}$, and seeks the member of $\mathcal{Q}$ closest to the true posterior in terms of the Kullback--Leibler (KL) divergence $^{28}$:
\[
\mathrm{KL}\bigl(q(\boldsymbol{\theta};\boldsymbol{\lambda}) \,\|\, p(\boldsymbol{\theta}\mid\mathbf{y})\bigr) = \mathbb{E}_q\!\left[\log\frac{q(\boldsymbol{\theta};\boldsymbol{\lambda})}{p(\boldsymbol{\theta}\mid\mathbf{y})}\right].
\]

Since $p(\boldsymbol{\theta}\mid\mathbf{y})$ is unavailable directly, minimizing the KL divergence is reformulated by decomposing the log marginal likelihood (the evidence) as
\[
\log p(\mathbf{y}) = \mathcal{L}(\boldsymbol{\lambda}) + \mathrm{KL}\bigl(q(\boldsymbol{\theta};\boldsymbol{\lambda})\,\|\,p(\boldsymbol{\theta}\mid\mathbf{y})\bigr),
\]
where $\mathcal{L}(\boldsymbol{\lambda})$ is the evidence lower bound (ELBO), defined as
\[
\mathcal{L}(\boldsymbol{\lambda}) = \mathbb{E}_q\bigl[\log p(\mathbf{y}, \boldsymbol{\theta})\bigr] - \mathbb{E}_q\bigl[\log q(\boldsymbol{\theta};\boldsymbol{\lambda})\bigr].
\]
Because $\log p(\mathbf{y})$ is constant with respect to $\boldsymbol{\lambda}$ and the KL divergence is non-negative, maximizing the ELBO is equivalent to minimizing the KL divergence, making the ELBO the central objective of variational inference $^{28,29}$.

A widely used approach within this framework is automatic differentiation variational inference (ADVI), implemented in Stan $^{29}$. ADVI automates VI by first applying a differentiable transformation $T: \Theta \to \mathbb{R}^d$ to map all constrained model parameters to an unconstrained space, and then fitting a Gaussian variational family in that transformed space---either a mean-field approximation with a diagonal covariance, or a full-rank approximation with a dense covariance matrix. Gradients of the ELBO with respect to $\boldsymbol{\lambda}$ are computed via automatic differentiation through Stan's computational graph, and the ELBO is maximized using stochastic gradient ascent, where Monte Carlo samples from $q$ are used to estimate the gradient at each iteration $^{29}$. This allows ADVI to be applied to any differentiable probabilistic model expressible in Stan without requiring model-specific derivations, making it a practical and scalable alternative to MCMC for large or complex models.

\subsubsection{Model Estimation and Tuning}

All models were estimated using mean-field variational inference (VI; \citealt{blei2017}) as implemented in the \texttt{rstanarm} package $^{30}$ within the R computing environment $^{31}$. The VI algorithm approximates the true posterior $p(\boldsymbol{\beta}, \sigma_\varepsilon \mid \mathbf{y}, \mathbf{X})$ by a product of independent Gaussian distributions (for unconstrained parameters), minimising the Kullback--Leibler divergence to the exact posterior. Each model was run with 1,000 posterior draws used for prediction and inference. Following advice from the RStanarm team, QR factorization is enabled when the number of observations in the training set is larger than or equal to the number of predictors; QR factorization improves numerical stability and the posterior fit in general and is the recommended approach. No further hyperparameter tuning was performed; the prior hyperparameters mentioned above were used as fixed defaults throughout.

\subsubsection{Performance Evaluation}

For each replication, the data were randomly split into a training set (80\% of observations) and a test set (20\%). Predictors were standardized using the training-set means and standard deviations, and the same transformation was applied to the test set. Predictive performance on the test set was quantified by the coefficient of determination,
\[
R^2 = 1 - \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n_{\text{test}}}(y_i - \hat{y}_i)^2}{\sum_{i=1}^{n_{\text{test}}}(y_i - \bar{y}_{\text{test}})^2},
\]
and the root mean squared error,
\[
\mathrm{RMSE} = \sqrt{\frac{1}{n_{\text{test}}}\sum_{i=1}^{n_{\text{test}}}(y_i - \hat{y}_i)^2},
\]
where $\hat{y}_i$ is the posterior mean prediction for observation $i$.

Variable selection was determined via 95\% credible intervals of the posterior distribution of each $\beta_j$. A predictor was considered selected if its credible interval did not contain zero, i.e., if $P(\hat{\beta}_j > 0 \mid \mathbf{y}) \geq 0.975$ or $P(\hat{\beta}_j < 0 \mid \mathbf{y}) \geq 0.975$.

Selection stability was assessed by the average pairwise Jaccard index across replications. For a given setting (prior, sample size, and layer), let $S_r$ be the set of selected predictors in replication $r$ ($r = 1, \ldots, R$). The Jaccard similarity between two sets is
\[
J(S_i, S_j) = \frac{|S_i \cap S_j|}{|S_i \cup S_j|},
\]
with $J(\emptyset, \emptyset) = 1$. The average and standard deviation of these pairwise indices,
\[
\bar{J} = \frac{2}{R(R-1)}\sum_{i<j} J(S_i, S_j), \qquad \mathrm{SD}(J) = \sqrt{\frac{2}{R(R-1)}\sum_{i<j}\bigl(J(S_i, S_j) - \bar{J}\bigr)^2},
\]
summarize the reproducibility of the selected sets.

\subsubsection{Simulation Parameters and Replications}

The design was a full factorial with three sample sizes ($n = 500, 2{,}000, 10{,}000$), two outcome layers (well-specified, misspecified), and three Bayesian prior specifications (normal, horseshoe, Laplace). The number of replications was 30. For each combination, predictive performance ($R^2$ and RMSE) and stability via the mean pairwise Jaccard index were computed. All simulation code was written in R. Results were summarized across replications by means and standard deviations of the performance measures.

