\section{Results}

The present Bayesian simulation study examined the predictive accuracy, variable selection properties, and selection stability of three prior specifications---horseshoe, Laplace (Bayesian lasso), and normal (ridge-type)---across three sample sizes ($n \in \{500, 2{,}000, 10{,}000\}$) and two model misspecification layers. The target of inference was a linear model with $p = 2{,}000$ predictors. Layer~1 represented the correctly specified linear model while Layer~2 incorporated quadratic, threshold, and interaction effects together with heteroscedastic noise. Up to 30 replications were planned per condition, but some fits failed due to numerical issues or exceeded computational resources. The actual number of successful replications for each combination is reported in Tables~\ref{tab:horseshoe}--\ref{tab:normal}.

\subsection{Predictive Performance}

Tables~\ref{tab:horseshoe}--\ref{tab:normal} display the mean $R^2$ and root mean squared error (RMSE) on the held-out test sets. For the horseshoe prior, predictive performance improved markedly with sample size. At $n = 500$, predictions were poor with mean $R^2$ values of $-0.026$ ($SD = 0.042$) for Layer~1 and $-0.027$ ($SD = 0.043$) for Layer~2, and RMSEs near 6.0. At $n = 2{,}000$, $R^2$ became slightly positive (Layer~1: $0.061$, $SD = 0.051$; Layer~2: $0.040$, $SD = 0.046$). With $n = 10{,}000$, the horseshoe prior achieved substantially better accuracy: $R^2$ for Layer~1 reached $.578$ ($SD = 0.130$) and for Layer~2 $.554$ ($SD = 0.235$), with RMSEs dropping to 3.90 and 3.98, respectively.

The Laplace prior yielded a similar pattern of improvement with increasing $n$, although at $n = 2{,}000$ in Layer~1 the results were compromised by extreme predictions in a subset of replications which led to mean $R^2$ and RMSE values on the order of $-4.0 \times 10^{33}$ and $6.8 \times 10^{16}$. These clearly reflect numerical instabilities rather than genuine model performance. Excluding that anomaly, the Laplace prior at $n = 500$ produced negative $R^2$ (Layer~1: $-0.018$, $SD = 0.047$; Layer~2: $-0.038$, $SD = 0.050$). At $n = 2{,}000$ Layer~2, $R^2$ was $.115$ ($SD = 0.044$). At $n = 10{,}000$, the Laplace prior performed comparably to the horseshoe with $R^2$ values of $.616$ (Layer~1) and $.589$ (Layer~2) and RMSEs of 3.76 and 3.89, respectively.

The normal prior, which applies only weak ridge-type shrinkage, produced extremely poor predictions at small and moderate sample sizes. For $n = 500$, mean $R^2$ was below $-9{,}000$ in both layers with very large RMSEs (e.g., Layer~1: $M = -9{,}408.81$, $SD = 2{,}758.55$). At $n = 2{,}000$, $R^2$ remained deeply negative. Even at $n = 10{,}000$, the normal prior failed to achieve positive $R^2$ with means of $-7.80$ (Layer~1) and $-1.07$ (Layer~2), and RMSEs of 14.17 and 8.66, respectively. Thus, the normal prior was unable to provide useful predictions across all conditions tested.

\subsection{Variable Selection}

The number of predictors selected (i.e., whose 95\% credible interval excluded zero) varied systematically with sample size and prior (Tables~\ref{tab:horseshoe}--\ref{tab:normal}). For the horseshoe prior, the mean number of selected variables approached the total $p = 2{,}000$ in most conditions. At $n = 2{,}000$, an average of 1,937 (Layer~1) and 1,789 (Layer~2) variables were selected, and at $n = 10{,}000$ these means were 1,978 and 1,972, respectively. The proportion of replications in which all 2,000 predictors were selected (\textit{prop\_all\_selected}) was above .90 for five of the six horseshoe conditions, indicating that the horseshoe prior did not induce strong sparsity in this high-dimensional setting.

The Laplace prior selected slightly fewer variables on average, with means of 1,725 (Layer~1) and 1,863 (Layer~2) at $n = 500$, which increased to around 1,940 at $n = 10{,}000$. The proportion of all-predictors-selected replications ranged from .72 to .90. The normal prior at $n = 10{,}000$ selected all 2,000 predictors in every successful replication, whereas at smaller sample sizes the mean number selected was lower but highly variable.

\subsection{Selection Stability}

Stability of the selected sets, quantified by the mean pairwise Jaccard index ($\bar{J}$), was generally high for all methods, reflecting the tendency to select nearly all predictors. For the horseshoe prior, $\bar{J}$ exceeded .90 in all conditions except $n = 500$ Layer~1 ($\bar{J} = .902$, $SD = .201$) and $n = 2{,}000$ Layer~2 ($\bar{J} = .801$, $SD = .269$). The Laplace prior showed similar stability with $\bar{J}$ ranging from .748 ($n = 500$ Layer~1) to .941 ($n = 10{,}000$ Layer~2). The normal prior's stability was perfect ($\bar{J} = 1.000$) at $n = 10{,}000$ because exactly all predictors were selected in every replication, whereas at lower sample sizes stability was lower. Overall, stability tended to increase with sample size and the variability of the Jaccard indices (SD) decreased correspondingly.







