\section{Discussion}

The present simulation evaluated three Bayesian shrinkage priors---horseshoe, Laplace, and normal---implemented via mean-field variational inference in \texttt{rstanarm} under both correctly specified linear models and compound misspecification. The results reveal a stark divergence between predictive accuracy and variable selection performance. At the largest sample size ($n = 10{,}000$), both the horseshoe and Laplace priors achieved moderately strong predictive accuracy with $R^2$ values exceeding .55 in both layers and RMSEs dropping substantially relative to smaller samples. This finding aligns with theoretical guarantees that heavy-tailed shrinkage priors can yield near-optimal prediction in high-dimensional regression even when the model is misspecified $^{3,7}$. Importantly, the severe nonlinearities, interactions, and heteroscedasticity of Layer~2 produced only modest degradation in predictive performance for these two priors, suggesting a degree of robustness consistent with recent work on Bayesian nonlinear regression under misspecification $^{8}$ and on robust variable selection with horseshoe-type priors $^{7}$.

In contrast, the normal (ridge-type) prior, which applies only weak Gaussian shrinkage, yielded catastrophic predictive performance across all sample sizes with $R^2$ remaining deeply negative even at $n = 10{,}000$. This emphasized that in $p \gg n$ settings, weak ridge-style regularization is insufficient to control overfitting when many predictors carry weak or no signal---a phenomenon well known in both frequentist and Bayesian literatures $^{9}$. The results thus reinforce the practical superiority of global--local shrinkage priors over simple normal priors in high dimensions.

Despite the promising predictive performance of the horseshoe and Laplace priors at large samples, variable selection based on 95\% credible intervals was strikingly uninformative. Across all conditions, the mean number of selected predictors approached the full set $p = 2{,}000$, and the proportion of replications in which all predictors were selected exceeded .80 in most cases. Even the Laplace prior, which is the Bayesian analogue of the lasso and is expected to induce sparsity $^{12}$, failed to reduce the selected set meaningfully. This contrasts sharply with the variable selection consistency typically claimed for these priors under idealized conditions $^{10,3}$. The near-absence of sparsity likely reflects several interacting factors. First, the default hyperpriors for the horseshoe and Laplace priors in \texttt{rstanarm} may not provide sufficiently strong global shrinkage when $p = 2{,}000$ and signals are dense but weak; the global shrinkage parameter $\tau$ requires careful tuning to achieve sparsity and its posterior under variational inference may be inadequately estimated $^{11}$. Second, mean-field variational inference, which approximates the posterior by a factorized Gaussian, tends to underestimate posterior variances and may fail to capture the heavy tails that drive shrinkage in these priors $^{28,24}$. Consequently, credible intervals remain wide enough to include zero for only a trivial fraction of coefficients, yielding selection of nearly all variables. This pattern mirrors concerns raised about the accuracy of variational approximations for sparse Bayesian models $^{19,18}$.

The Laplace prior exhibited severe numerical instability in the $n = 2{,}000$ Layer~1 condition, which produced implausible $R^2$ and RMSE values on the order of $10^{33}$ and $10^{16}$. Such instability likely stems from convergence failures in the stochastic optimization of the ELBO when the posterior geometry is challenging---an issue documented in VI applications to high-dimensional regression $^{19,22}$. These failures highlight that the computational reliability of default VI implementations cannot be taken for granted, particularly at moderate sample sizes where the likelihood is less informative relative to the prior.

Selection stability as measured by the mean pairwise Jaccard index was consistently high across methods and conditions, often exceeding .90. However, this high stability is a direct consequence of the tendency to select all or nearly all predictors. When the selected set is almost always the full set, the Jaccard index is necessarily near 1. Thus, the stability metric provides little discriminative information in this study and should be interpreted with caution. The observed decreases in Jaccard stability at smaller sample sizes (e.g., Laplace at $n = 500$) correspond to greater variability in the subset of predictors that happen to fall below the selection threshold, reflecting heightened posterior uncertainty rather than meaningful model selection consistency.

%-----------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Implications}

The present findings carry several implications for applied researchers who rely on Bayesian shrinkage methods via accessible software such as \texttt{rstanarm}. First, when prediction is the primary goal, the horseshoe and Laplace priors with variational inference can deliver robust performance even under substantial model misspecification, provided that the sample size is sufficiently large ($n = 10{,}000$ in our design). This makes them viable tools for large-scale predictive modeling in psychology and social sciences where complex nonlinearities and heteroscedasticity are common but may not need to be explicitly modeled. Second, the default variational inference implementation in \texttt{rstanarm} with its fixed hyperpriors and mean-field approximation should not be relied upon for variable selection in high dimensions. Researchers who need to identify a sparse set of important predictors must either (a) tune the hyperpriors carefully, such as by adjusting the global scale of the horseshoe $^{11}$, (b) switch to full Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) sampling, which can better capture the posterior tails and thus produce sharper credible intervals $^{18}$, or (c) employ alternative software specifically designed for sparse Bayesian variable selection, such as those using spike-and-slab priors with dedicated stochastic search algorithms $^{24}$. Third, the catastrophic failure of the normal prior at all sample sizes serves as a cautionary tale. Weakly regularized Gaussian priors are entirely inadequate for high-dimensional regression and should be avoided unless strong prior information justifies a dense solution.

More broadly, the present study demonstrates that variational inference, while computationally attractive, can mask the inferential strengths of theoretically well-motivated priors. The gap between the theoretical properties of the horseshoe and Laplace priors $^{10,12}$ and their practical performance under default VI settings underscores the need for careful validation of approximate inference algorithms in realistic data scenarios. The companion frequentist benchmark $^{1}$ further allows a direct comparison of penalized maximum-likelihood methods with Bayesian VI approaches under identical data-generating conditions, offering guidance for method selection based on analytic goals.

%-----------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Limitations and Future Directions}

Several limitations of the present study point to avenues for future research. First, only 30 replications were planned and some conditions had fewer successful runs due to convergence failures. This reduces the precision of summary statistics and precludes formal statistical comparisons between methods. Larger replication counts would be necessary for definitive conclusions. Second, the simulation considered only one covariance structure (block-diagonal with $\rho = 0.4$) and one set of fixed effect sizes. The generalizability to other correlation patterns and sparsity levels is unknown. Third, the planned spike-and-slab prior was not included in the final analysis due to computational constraints, which leaves open the question of whether a fully Bayesian model-averaging approach would improve variable selection under VI. Fourth, we used the default hyperparameter settings without any tuning; systematic optimization of the prior hyperparameters (e.g., the global shrinkage scale) might substantially improve sparsity and prediction, but would require additional computational cost. Fifth, the mean-field approximation is known to be a crude approximation to the true posterior, especially for priors with strong dependencies. Future work should compare mean-field VI with full-rank VI or with MCMC to isolate the effects of the approximation $^{28,29}$. Sixth, the computational failures encountered with the Laplace prior at $n = 2{,}000$ warrant detailed investigation of the ELBO optimization landscape and possible remedies, such as better initialization, adaptive step-size schedules, or alternative divergence measures $^{4}$. Finally, integrating these Bayesian results with the frequentist benchmark $^{1}$ would provide a comprehensive view of the relative strengths of penalized likelihood and Bayesian shrinkage methods under misspecification, enabling evidence-based recommendations for applied researchers.

%-----------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Conclusion}

The present study benchmarked three Bayesian shrinkage priors---horseshoe, Laplace, and normal---implemented through mean-field variational inference in \texttt{rstanarm} under both a well-specified linear model and a deliberately misspecified model featuring nonlinearity, interactions, and heteroscedasticity. At large sample sizes, the horseshoe and Laplace priors provided robust predictive accuracy whereas the normal prior failed entirely. However, none of the methods achieved meaningful variable selection. The credible intervals under default VI settings selected almost all predictors, yielding spurious completeness. These results underscore that the default variational inference pipeline in \texttt{rstanarm} is suitable for prediction in high dimensions when sample sizes are large, but is unreliable for variable selection without further tuning or the use of more accurate posterior approximations. As Bayesian software becomes increasingly accessible, careful evaluation of the interplay between prior specification, approximate inference algorithms, and study goals is essential to avoid overconfident or misleading inferences. The present work contributes a much-needed empirical perspective to this evaluation and sets the stage for more nuanced methodological guidance.

